1
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,430
<i>"I lost no time, of course, in
telling my mother all that I knew...</i>

2
00:00:24,500 --> 00:00:28,430
<i>"and we saw ourselves at once in
a difficult and dangerous position.</i>

3
00:00:28,500 --> 00:00:31,730
<i>"Something must speedily be resolved
upon, and it occurred to us...</i>

4
00:00:31,790 --> 00:00:33,390
"at last to go forth together...

5
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:35,400
"and seek help
in the neighboring hamlet.

6
00:00:35,990 --> 00:00:39,110
"No sooner said than done.
Bare-headed as we were...

7
00:00:39,310 --> 00:00:43,090
"we ran out at once in the gathering
evening and the frosty fog.

8
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:45,770
"The hamlet lay not many
hundred yards away...

9
00:00:45,850 --> 00:00:48,710
<i>"though out of view, on the other
side of the next cove...</i>

10
00:00:48,790 --> 00:00:50,510
<i>"and what greatly encouraged me...</i>

11
00:00:50,580 --> 00:00:52,140
"it was in an opposite direction...

12
00:00:52,220 --> 00:00:55,210
"from that whence the blind man
had made his appearance.

13
00:00:55,280 --> 00:00:57,490
"And I shall never forget
how much I was cheered...

14
00:00:57,560 --> 00:01:00,370
"to see the yellow shine in doors
and windows...

15
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:01,480
<i>"but that, as it proved...</i>

16
00:01:01,560 --> 00:01:04,860
<i>"was the best of the help we were
likely to get in that quarter.</i>

17
00:01:04,910 --> 00:01:06,230
<i>"For you would have thought...</i>

18
00:01:06,300 --> 00:01:08,150
<i>"men would have been
ashamed of themselves...</i>

19
00:01:08,210 --> 00:01:11,280
<i>"no soul would consent
to return with us to the..."</i>

20
00:01:32,060 --> 00:01:33,520
Audrey? Sorry.

21
00:01:35,770 --> 00:01:37,460
Mr. Talcott's gone.

22
00:01:38,690 --> 00:01:39,630
Okay.

23
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,340
Front desk, in case anyone shows.

24
00:02:05,750 --> 00:02:08,000
I think you'll be waiting
a while, hon.

25
00:02:08,260 --> 00:02:11,000
No. Didn't we call? He said he had family.

26
00:02:11,070 --> 00:02:12,060
Yeah.

27
00:02:12,120 --> 00:02:15,220
But they don't wanna have anything
to do with him.

28
00:02:15,330 --> 00:02:17,240
You can dump it out back.

29
00:03:27,140 --> 00:03:28,770
Okay, take a look.

30
00:03:31,370 --> 00:03:33,060
I interview tomorrow.

31
00:03:33,130 --> 00:03:34,240
What about your job?

32
00:03:34,320 --> 00:03:35,690
I had enough of that place.

33
00:03:35,750 --> 00:03:37,510
What happened?
Here's your beer.

34
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:39,820
- Thanks.
- Sure.

35
00:03:40,490 --> 00:03:43,270
I lost a patient today. Mr. Talcott.

36
00:03:43,560 --> 00:03:45,450
- I'm sorry.
- You should have seen it.

37
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:46,950
The second he died, it was like...

38
00:03:47,020 --> 00:03:48,580
they couldn't wait to get him out of there.

39
00:03:48,650 --> 00:03:49,860
It's just a business to them.

40
00:03:49,930 --> 00:03:51,620
It is a business, but at least he had you.

41
00:03:51,700 --> 00:03:54,000
No. It's supposed to be
a business about caring.

42
00:03:54,060 --> 00:03:55,140
They couldn't care less.

43
00:03:56,460 --> 00:04:00,070
Wait. This is Terrebonne Parish.
It's the freaking swamps.

44
00:04:01,010 --> 00:04:04,490
I get the hours I need to start
nursing school, and I get paid.

45
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:07,560
And I get to help somebody, my way.

46
00:04:07,690 --> 00:04:10,960
They got gators in the swamps,
and guys missing teeth.

47
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:13,350
Are we dancing here, or what?

48
00:04:14,480 --> 00:04:15,820
Cary, look.

49
00:04:15,920 --> 00:04:18,670
This work you're doing,
are you sure it's not changing you?

50
00:04:18,730 --> 00:04:21,320
I'm 25 years old.
What's wrong with a little change?

51
00:05:50,390 --> 00:05:51,740
Oh, my God.

52
00:06:23,100 --> 00:06:24,250
Hello?

53
00:06:29,030 --> 00:06:30,170
Hello?

54
00:07:24,100 --> 00:07:26,630
Now that right there
is what love is all about.

55
00:07:26,690 --> 00:07:29,510
Old-fashioned devotion,
like what you read about.

56
00:07:29,870 --> 00:07:31,360
You must be Caroline.

57
00:07:31,430 --> 00:07:34,050
I'm sorry, the door was open,
so I just walked in.

58
00:07:34,130 --> 00:07:36,580
Oh, no. It's a big house. I didn't hear you.

59
00:07:38,180 --> 00:07:39,130
It's okay.

60
00:07:41,070 --> 00:07:43,530
So much for getting their affairs in order.

61
00:07:44,270 --> 00:07:47,840
I'm sorry. I'm Luke Marshall. Estate lawyer.

62
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:49,690
We talked on the phone.

63
00:07:49,770 --> 00:07:51,050
Oh, right.

64
00:07:52,330 --> 00:07:55,430
The docs figure a month maybe.
He's pretty far gone.

65
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:56,550
I understand.

66
00:07:56,620 --> 00:07:59,690
His wife's having kind of
a rough time with it.

67
00:08:00,140 --> 00:08:01,550
Most people do.

68
00:08:05,480 --> 00:08:07,560
Violet, you have a visitor.

69
00:08:10,580 --> 00:08:12,360
May I present Miss Caroline Ellis?

70
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:14,060
She works down at the hospice
in New Orleans.

71
00:08:14,120 --> 00:08:16,100
Caroline, this is Violet Devereaux.

72
00:08:17,620 --> 00:08:19,470
You have a lovely home.

73
00:08:26,190 --> 00:08:28,710
I'm sorry. It's just hard.
The idea of a stranger living here...

74
00:08:28,790 --> 00:08:30,090
I understand, really.

75
00:08:30,160 --> 00:08:33,230
She's Old South, you know.
She thinks women still curtsey.

76
00:08:36,410 --> 00:08:38,340
So, he can't talk at all?

77
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:41,040
No. Stroke pretty much paralyzed him.

78
00:08:41,110 --> 00:08:43,340
- Which side was affected?
- Both.

79
00:08:43,930 --> 00:08:46,890
It happened about a month ago,
up in the attic.

80
00:08:47,090 --> 00:08:49,070
That's where she found him.

81
00:08:49,140 --> 00:08:50,190
Ben?

82
00:08:51,540 --> 00:08:54,410
You have a visitor. Meet Miss Caroline Ellis.

83
00:08:55,090 --> 00:08:57,230
Hello, Ben. I'm Caroline.

84
00:08:59,090 --> 00:09:02,500
She's not from around here.
She not gonna understand my house.

85
00:09:02,580 --> 00:09:03,720
She's from New Orleans.

86
00:09:03,800 --> 00:09:06,800
She wasn't raised in New Orleans.
You hear how she talks?

87
00:09:07,160 --> 00:09:10,230
Who knows where she comes from?
Hoboken, New Jersey.

88
00:09:11,160 --> 00:09:13,200
What do you want a Southern accent?

89
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:15,380
The last one left, Violet.

90
00:09:15,890 --> 00:09:17,170
All right.

91
00:09:18,480 --> 00:09:21,140
But she's not gonna understand the house.

92
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:23,430
The last girl left, huh?

93
00:09:23,510 --> 00:09:25,940
Wait. Let me talk to her,
we can straighten things out.

94
00:09:26,010 --> 00:09:28,050
I can't help anybody
who doesn't want my help.

95
00:09:28,120 --> 00:09:30,200
She does want help. She's just scared.

96
00:09:30,260 --> 00:09:31,790
Of what? Politeness?

97
00:09:31,870 --> 00:09:34,000
No. He's the love of her life and he's dying.

98
00:09:34,070 --> 00:09:35,570
They've been together forever.

99
00:09:35,640 --> 00:09:37,300
She's losing her soul mate here.

100
00:09:37,370 --> 00:09:39,890
I don't know about you, but that'd
put some sandpaper up my ass.

101
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:41,750
Aren't you a romantic?

102
00:09:43,710 --> 00:09:44,760
Look.

103
00:09:44,890 --> 00:09:46,170
The last girl quit.

104
00:09:46,230 --> 00:09:48,340
You're the fifth interview since.
She shoots down everyone.

105
00:09:49,820 --> 00:09:51,380
It's not personal.

106
00:09:51,450 --> 00:09:53,630
But you being here means he's really dying.

107
00:09:56,540 --> 00:09:58,960
He's dying whether I'm here or not.

108
00:09:59,830 --> 00:10:02,110
What'd she mean about the house?

109
00:10:02,630 --> 00:10:03,630
What?

110
00:10:03,710 --> 00:10:07,420
She said I wouldn't understand
the house. Why'd she said that?

111
00:10:08,350 --> 00:10:10,590
All I know is her checks clear.

112
00:10:11,490 --> 00:10:13,050
Look, forget it.

113
00:10:13,380 --> 00:10:17,090
If it makes you feel any better, I'm
still looking for my dream job, too.

114
00:10:18,020 --> 00:10:18,970
All right.

115
00:10:20,610 --> 00:10:23,260
So if you talked to her, what would you say?

116
00:10:24,960 --> 00:10:26,940
I'd say she could look all she wants...

117
00:10:27,010 --> 00:10:29,350
but I doubt she'd find any better than you.

118
00:10:29,790 --> 00:10:32,310
So she'd do well to treat you like it.

119
00:10:34,090 --> 00:10:37,120
Okay, here are my rules. No knitting.

120
00:10:38,140 --> 00:10:40,090
No joining a bridge club.

121
00:10:40,320 --> 00:10:41,910
And no playing bingo.

122
00:10:42,280 --> 00:10:44,220
Okay, good. Good rules.

123
00:10:44,700 --> 00:10:47,750
I'm serious, they'll try and suck
you into their elderly ways.

124
00:10:47,810 --> 00:10:50,050
It's less than an hour away.
I'll be back all the time.

125
00:10:50,110 --> 00:10:51,580
Yeah, well, you better.

126
00:10:51,650 --> 00:10:54,720
Whenever you want to talk to someone
who wasn't around for World War II.

127
00:10:54,790 --> 00:10:57,030
Jeez, what is it with you and old people?

128
00:10:57,100 --> 00:10:58,050
Come here.

129
00:10:58,790 --> 00:11:01,410
He'd be proud of you. You know he would.

130
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:29,340
Hello?

131
00:11:35,270 --> 00:11:37,320
I need to pay for some gas.

132
00:11:44,110 --> 00:11:45,220
Hello?

133
00:12:05,230 --> 00:12:07,090
Is somebody back there?

134
00:12:23,130 --> 00:12:24,430
I'm sorry.

135
00:12:25,360 --> 00:12:28,110
Excuse me. I just need to pay for some gas.

136
00:12:41,940 --> 00:12:42,950
Jesus.

137
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:52,000
Upcoming jump scare (Minor)

138
00:12:55,160 --> 00:12:56,880
$17 for the gas.

139
00:12:59,480 --> 00:13:01,040
Keep the change.

140
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:17,000
Upcoming jump scare (Major)

141
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,500
Mrs. Devereaux?

142
00:13:49,760 --> 00:13:51,190
I'm unpacked.

143
00:14:13,630 --> 00:14:16,060
Hi, Ben. Remember me? I'm Caroline.

144
00:14:16,770 --> 00:14:18,810
I'll be taking care of you for a while.

145
00:14:25,150 --> 00:14:28,060
There's not a lot of light in here
for you, is there?

146
00:14:31,170 --> 00:14:33,560
So you're a fan of the blues, huh?
Well, so was...

147
00:14:35,040 --> 00:14:36,740
You have to let go.

148
00:14:37,310 --> 00:14:39,070
Ben, you're hurting me.

149
00:14:39,140 --> 00:14:40,150
Ouch.

150
00:14:40,230 --> 00:14:41,660
There you are.

151
00:14:41,730 --> 00:14:43,560
Time for his remedies.

152
00:14:44,350 --> 00:14:45,980
Scoot over, child.

153
00:14:46,890 --> 00:14:49,270
9:00 in the morning and 7:00 at night.

154
00:14:49,350 --> 00:14:52,610
He takes his pills in powder form.
I'll show you how.

155
00:14:52,680 --> 00:14:54,650
Be sure he drinks it all down.

156
00:14:54,720 --> 00:14:57,450
What's he taking?
Oh, Coumadin and such.

157
00:14:57,610 --> 00:15:00,960
He gets the tremors sometimes.
Don't let that frighten you.

158
00:15:02,540 --> 00:15:04,770
And a kiss to make it taste better.

159
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:13,000
Upcoming jump scare (Minor)
You're scrawnier than I'd hoped.
Prettier, though.
I bet you're all marked up, aren't you?

160
00:15:14,020 --> 00:15:15,880
- Marked up?
- Written on.

161
00:15:16,170 --> 00:15:17,540
I know you young people are always...

162
00:15:17,610 --> 00:15:20,200
jabbing yourselves with ink and needles.

163
00:15:20,550 --> 00:15:22,180
You're written on, aren't you?

164
00:15:22,410 --> 00:15:24,240
Not where you can see.

165
00:15:24,330 --> 00:15:25,280
Well.

166
00:15:25,740 --> 00:15:28,710
He's to be bathed daily, his linens changed.

167
00:15:29,130 --> 00:15:32,740
Don't bother with the housework.
I'm the only one that knows how.

168
00:15:34,150 --> 00:15:36,490
How long have you two lived here?

169
00:15:37,960 --> 00:15:39,280
Let's see.

170
00:15:39,880 --> 00:15:42,990
We came over from Savannah in '62.

171
00:15:43,820 --> 00:15:46,720
We bought this house
from a brother and a sister.

172
00:15:46,830 --> 00:15:49,990
They'd inherited it a long time ago,
from their parents.

173
00:15:50,350 --> 00:15:52,490
Lived here since they were children.

174
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:54,890
There they are. Martin and Grace.

175
00:15:55,600 --> 00:15:57,150
Charming people.

176
00:15:58,160 --> 00:16:01,330
But they fell on hard times, had to sell.

177
00:16:01,840 --> 00:16:03,490
You keep their picture?

178
00:16:03,570 --> 00:16:07,240
Yes. I like to pay my respects
to the memories of this house.

179
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:23,690
All right. Come along now.

180
00:16:30,420 --> 00:16:32,170
This is the dining room.

181
00:16:32,240 --> 00:16:33,870
We only use about half of the rooms.

182
00:16:33,940 --> 00:16:36,110
The others are for Ben's antique business.

183
00:16:36,340 --> 00:16:38,930
What he couldn't sell, we stored here.

184
00:16:38,990 --> 00:16:40,900
Except for the attic.

185
00:16:41,070 --> 00:16:43,050
That has crystal and china.

186
00:16:43,130 --> 00:16:46,640
And I keep a very close account
on that, just so as you know.

187
00:16:49,720 --> 00:16:52,170
There are more than 30 rooms in all.

188
00:16:52,370 --> 00:16:55,790
In the old days, they made
a separate key for each room.

189
00:16:55,870 --> 00:16:58,930
For the owner, they made a skeleton key.

190
00:16:59,860 --> 00:17:01,800
This will open every door.

191
00:17:02,430 --> 00:17:04,020
This one is yours.

192
00:17:05,240 --> 00:17:06,620
I have mine.

193
00:17:07,990 --> 00:17:09,780
Now, the pantry's right out here.

194
00:17:09,850 --> 00:17:13,490
You know, we may have to ask you
to go into town now and then.

195
00:17:13,560 --> 00:17:15,410
Was there a mirror here once?

196
00:17:17,820 --> 00:17:20,370
I noticed in the bathrooms also
there are no mirrors.

197
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:23,440
Child, when you get as worn-out
and wrinkled as we are...

198
00:17:23,520 --> 00:17:25,210
you don't need any reminding.

199
00:17:25,270 --> 00:17:27,320
If you want a small one
for your own purposes...

200
00:17:27,380 --> 00:17:28,440
that's fine with me.

201
00:17:28,510 --> 00:17:31,220
- What'd you do with them?
- Put them away.

202
00:17:36,740 --> 00:17:39,070
The boy tells me you don't smoke.

203
00:17:39,200 --> 00:17:42,160
I do smoke. I smoke a lot
and I enjoy it very much.

204
00:17:42,240 --> 00:17:43,670
I trust that won't be an issue.

205
00:17:43,740 --> 00:17:44,730
It won't be.

206
00:17:44,790 --> 00:17:47,220
Good. Then for the most part
just realize that...

207
00:17:47,300 --> 00:17:49,370
I'll live here as if you're not in residence.

208
00:17:49,430 --> 00:17:52,750
After all, we're not kin.
Are your parents still alive?

209
00:17:53,910 --> 00:17:58,170
My mom left when I was little. My
dad raised me and he died last year.

210
00:17:58,560 --> 00:18:01,560
Oh, my. So you cared for him as well?

211
00:18:03,070 --> 00:18:04,500
I would have.

212
00:18:04,770 --> 00:18:07,010
I just thought I had more time.

213
00:18:10,020 --> 00:18:11,060
Yeah.

214
00:18:12,030 --> 00:18:15,130
You think too much about the time
you have left...

215
00:18:15,650 --> 00:18:17,620
you don't spend it living.

216
00:18:17,860 --> 00:18:20,790
Be good to my husband.
Be good to his house.

217
00:18:21,470 --> 00:18:22,790
Remedies at 9:00.

218
00:18:22,880 --> 00:18:24,890
One, two, three.

219
00:18:43,560 --> 00:18:47,230
You don't see gardens like this
back in New Jersey, I expect.

220
00:18:48,450 --> 00:18:50,730
Actually, it's the Garden State.

221
00:18:51,230 --> 00:18:53,180
I doubt that very much.

222
00:18:54,820 --> 00:18:57,280
Nothing more glorious than a garden.

223
00:18:57,350 --> 00:18:59,810
Gone every winter, back every spring.

224
00:19:03,180 --> 00:19:04,930
You religious at all?

225
00:19:06,050 --> 00:19:08,100
I try to keep an open mind.

226
00:19:08,420 --> 00:19:10,400
That's good. That's very good.

227
00:19:11,630 --> 00:19:13,290
Where are my trilliums?

228
00:19:13,350 --> 00:19:16,520
Oh, fiddlesticks. Do me a blessing, child.

229
00:19:16,900 --> 00:19:18,720
Will you run up to the attic for me?

230
00:19:18,790 --> 00:19:22,370
I have some seed packets in a box
right next to the stairs.

231
00:22:07,710 --> 00:22:09,180
What took you?

232
00:22:10,300 --> 00:22:11,610
I'm sorry.

233
00:22:12,670 --> 00:22:15,100
I thought the key opens everything.

234
00:22:15,390 --> 00:22:17,370
The key? What key?

235
00:22:17,450 --> 00:22:19,330
The key you gave me for the house.

236
00:22:19,390 --> 00:22:21,670
There's a door in the attic
it doesn't work for.

237
00:22:22,600 --> 00:22:25,340
Oh, no, the attic, it's never opened that.

238
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:34,000
Upcoming jump scare (Minor)
- I got my Dixie-Johns.
- Why not?
- What's in there?
- I have no idea.
It's been shut ever since we moved in.

239
00:22:35,560 --> 00:22:39,330
I have to get these in the ground,
because there's rain coming.

240
00:22:39,430 --> 00:22:40,990
Mrs. Devereaux...

241
00:22:41,060 --> 00:22:44,480
Ben was in the attic, wasn't he,
when he had his stroke?

242
00:22:48,510 --> 00:22:50,560
What was he doing in there?

243
00:22:50,760 --> 00:22:52,930
You'll have to ask him, child.

244
00:22:54,060 --> 00:22:56,610
Be a dear and go see to him, won't you?

245
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:04,000
Upcoming jump scare (Major)
I wonder if he wouldn't like some iced tea.

246
00:25:08,820 --> 00:25:10,550
His door was locked.

247
00:25:13,150 --> 00:25:14,190
Ben!

248
00:25:22,390 --> 00:25:23,670
Ben!

249
00:25:25,530 --> 00:25:26,740
Ben!

250
00:25:29,380 --> 00:25:32,750
Stop right there, Ben! Don't move!

251
00:25:40,220 --> 00:25:41,300
Stop!

252
00:25:42,790 --> 00:25:43,730
Ben!

253
00:25:47,420 --> 00:25:48,910
Mrs. Devereaux!

254
00:25:55,960 --> 00:25:56,980
Ben!

